<img src=http://www.theholystorm.org/gifs/dunwut-banner.jpg></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/bemarr.showUserPublicProfile?gid=theodwynriddermark>TheodwynRiddermark</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 397<br> <font color=#E9D756>(11/4/02 4:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3774.topic&index=52>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Comments.....</span><hr size=1> I don't know any of the people involved, so I can't make any character support or defamation remarks.<br>
<br>
But I think it might be worthwhile to make some comments about the mantle of leadership and officership.<br>
<br>
Being an authority figure of a guild in EQ is a heavy responsibility.  Just like real life.  It is a burden, but with immeasurable potential for rewards.<br>
<br>
The leadership skill is the same both in game and out of it.  It requires integrity.  It requires commitment.  It requires a certain amount of guts and resolve.  And it absolutely requires communication.<br>
<br>
A good leader is a good follower, and understands both sides of the coin.  When to be autocratic, when to be compromising, when to be obedient.<br>
<br>
Leadership requires tact.  You can say almost anything to anyone if you can say it in a manner that is respectful to them.  If I cannot answer your tell right now, I will tell you why.  If I feel it is not the time and place for your discussion, I will suggest taking it to e-mail.  It is always better to set your boundaries in order to avoid starting shitstorms.  A leader who embroils in a shitstorm always looks bad, even if they're right.<br>
<br>
I have in my role found myself in situations of unproductive tell hell on several an occassion.  I have suggested taking it offline.  Now, &quot;taking it offline&quot; does not mean &quot;blowing you off&quot;.  I make sure the other party knows that.  It's a very important distinction.<br>
<br>
Leaders have a responsibility to show their commitment to the welfare of the people under their command.  Even if you don't have time for it.  Even if you're pissed at them at the moment.  You can tell them off if you can remind them that you care about them in the process.  ie.  &quot;I do want to discuss this with you, but now is not the time or place.  Send me an e-mail, let's talk&quot;.<br>
<br>
Now, followers have the responsibility of deferring to their leaders when demanded of them.  If you don't like your leader, leave.  You have the power to pick and choose if you're going to put up with it or not.  Choose your leaders carefully.  If you know they will make unreasonable demands of you, be bigger than that.  Don't whine, don't complain.  In the end, you are your own leader.  Set yourself a good example.  If you have more class than the person with the guild officer tag, show them.<br>
<br>
Those are my only tidbits to share.<br>
<br>
But something mentioned recently gave me pause.....<br>
<br>
Sagemon's post.  Sage and I have disagreed on occassion.  But I have always respected his position.  He does not lie.  His post concerns and saddens me.  I know some really good people in AToF, and if what I have read is to be believed, I feel for them.<br>
<br>
Theo<br>
